markdown: <::A lithograph by David Hockney titled "A Garden". The artwork depicts a lush garden scene with a central architectural structure resembling a gazebo or small building with a balcony. Two figures, possibly women, are visible in the garden, one on the left partially obscured by foliage and another on the right in a long dress. The scene is framed by an ornate border of roses and butterflies. The overall style is detailed and decorative, characteristic of a lithograph.::> HOCKNEY 77 10/100 DAVID HOCKNEY, R.A. (b. 1937) A Garden, lithograph, signed and dated, 1977, 700 x 990 mm. Desmond Heeley's design for Don Pasquale. Limited edition of 500, numbered and signed by Mr. Heeley. 19½"x25". $35(1.00)#E35 In gold metal frame ready for hanging: $80(2.50)#E35F Antique Opera Purses These elegant English Sterling Silver purses date from 1890 to about 1918. Each has been handsomely relined in leather, and has a contemporary Sterling Silver chain. These one-of-a-kind antiques are about 41/2" long, with some bearing the initials of their original owners. $450(1.75)#G63 The Carmen Scarves Based on the shawl worn at the Met by Geraldine Ferrar as Carmen, these 32" hand-rolled crepe de Chine scarves are available in beige, or a striking black background, and come in a deluxe gift envelope. $25(1.00) Beige: #G11B Black: #G11C <::A black and white photograph shows two ornate silver purses or bags with intricate floral and scroll engravings. The purse on the left is open, revealing a dark interior, and has a rounded, somewhat rectangular shape. The purse on the right is closed, has a more angular, scalloped top edge, and also features detailed engravings. Both purses have delicate chains attached. They are resting on a light-colored fabric with a subtle floral or leaf pattern. In the bottom right corner of the image, there is a smaller inset photograph showing two square pieces of fabric, possibly handkerchiefs or swatches. The left fabric piece is light-colored with a central floral design, and the right piece is dark-colored with a similar floral design. A small number "3" is visible in the bottom right of the inset image. : figure::> Source: https://www.industrydocuments.ucsf.edu/docs/njnp0227 <::Two square embroidered cloths are shown, one light-colored and one dark-colored, both featuring a central floral design with a large rose and surrounding smaller flowers and leaves, and a decorative border. The light-colored cloth is positioned in front and slightly to the left of the dark-colored cloth. The number '3' is visible in the bottom right corner. : figure::> Source: https://www.industrydocuments.ucsf.edu/docs/njnp0227
